</taxonomicNameLabel>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F75B07F081E3739A1FDD4B7CA1F70" authority="Dejean" authorityName="Dejean" box="[505,748,520,545]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Purpuricenus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95BD2217F081E3739A1FDD4B7B71F71" box="[505,657,521,544]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="400">Purpuricenus</emphasis>
Dejean
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F75B07F081E373B43FDD4B16B1F70" authority="Audinet-Serville" authorityName="Audinet-Serville" box="[795,1101,520,545]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Stenaspis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95BD2217F081E373B43FDD4B6A31F71" box="[795,901,521,544]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="400">Stenaspis</emphasis>
Audinet-Serville
</taxonomicName>
) include: (
<number id="3DE71C147F081E373C88FDD4B1FD1F70" box="[1232,1243,521,545]" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" value="1.0">1</number>
) long erect hair covering the entire body (i.e, especially on femora, tibia, and elytra); (
<number id="3DE71C147F081E373B87FDF0B6C81F14" box="[991,1006,557,581]" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" value="2.0">2</number>
) coarsely and contiguously punctate dorsum (i.e., on the vertex, pronotum and elytra (
<figureCitation id="131412B67F081E373AE2FD8DB6301F38" box="[698,790,592,617]" captionStart="FIGURES 25 – 28" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1873,1895]" captionTargetBox="[256,1334,845,1846]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[246,1340,845,1851]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 25 – 28. Comparison of structural characters of Pilostenaspis and Stenaspis: 25, 26: Pilostenaspis copei (female), 25 a, 25 b, 25 c: vertex, prothorax and elytra, respectively, coarsely and contiguously punctate; 26 a: prosternal intercoxal process protuberant; 26 b: mesosternal intercoxal process protuberant or subtuberculiform. 27, 28: Stenaspis castaneipennis Dupont (male), 27: dorsum glabrate; 28 a: prosternal intercoxal process protuberant, ridged between coxae, and vertical behind." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242651/files/figure.png" pageId="49" pageNumber="400">
Figs. 
<number id="3DE71C147F081E373AA1FD8DB6301F38" box="[761,790,592,617]" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" value="25.0">25</number>
</figureCitation>
a– 
<number id="3DE71C147F081E373B6BFD8DB6761F38" box="[819,848,592,617]" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" value="25.0">25</number>
c); (
<number id="3DE71C147F081E373B21FD8CB6A11F38" box="[889,903,593,617]" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" value="3.0">3</number>
) densely, deeply punctate femora and tibia; and (
<number id="3DE71C147F081E3738C7FDA8B5881FDC" box="[159,174,629,653]" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" value="4.0">4</number>
) elytra that are not costate (i.e., vaguely costate on 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F75B07F081E373AA3FDA8B6F61FDD" box="[763,976,629,652]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Megapurpuricenus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95BD2217F081E373AA3FDA8B6F61FDD" box="[763,976,629,652]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="400">Megapurpuricenus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). These three species (i.e., 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F75B07F081E373D5EFDA9B5F21FE1" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Pilostenaspis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="copei">
<emphasis id="B95BD2217F081E373D5EFDA9B5F21FE1" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="400">Pilostenaspis copei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F75B07F081E3738B9FD44B47C1FE0" box="[225,346,664,689]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Pilostenaspis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lateralis">
<emphasis id="B95BD2217F081E3738B9FD44B5C91FE1" box="[225,239,665,688]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="400">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B95BD2217F081E3738A5FD45B47C1FE0" box="[253,346,664,689]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="400">lateralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F75B07F081E3739CFFD44B7321FE0" box="[407,532,664,689]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Stenaspis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosella">
<emphasis id="B95BD2217F081E3739CFFD44B4831FE1" box="[407,421,665,688]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="400">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B95BD2217F081E3739EBFD45B7321FE0" box="[435,532,664,689]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="400">pilosella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) also have the lateral margins of the pronotum and elytra that are reddish, and an intercoxal process of both pro- and mesosternum that are protuberant or subtuberculiform (
<figureCitation id="131412B67F081E373CBDFD61B06E1F84" box="[1253,1352,700,725]" captionStart="FIGURES 25 – 28" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1873,1895]" captionTargetBox="[256,1334,845,1846]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[246,1340,845,1851]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 25 – 28. Comparison of structural characters of Pilostenaspis and Stenaspis: 25, 26: Pilostenaspis copei (female), 25 a, 25 b, 25 c: vertex, prothorax and elytra, respectively, coarsely and contiguously punctate; 26 a: prosternal intercoxal process protuberant; 26 b: mesosternal intercoxal process protuberant or subtuberculiform. 27, 28: Stenaspis castaneipennis Dupont (male), 27: dorsum glabrate; 28 a: prosternal intercoxal process protuberant, ridged between coxae, and vertical behind." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242651/files/figure.png" pageId="49" pageNumber="400">
Figs. 
<number id="3DE71C147F081E373D73FD61B06E1F84" box="[1323,1352,700,725]" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" value="26.0">26</number>
</figureCitation>
a– 
<number id="3DE71C147F081E373D3DFD61B0A41F84" box="[1381,1410,700,725]" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" value="26.0">26</number>
b). According to a comment made by Bates in his description for 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F75B07F081E373B3CFD3CB1131FA8" box="[868,1077,736,761]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Stenaspis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosella">
<emphasis id="B95BD2217F081E373B3CFD3CB1131FA8" box="[868,1077,736,761]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="400">Stenaspis pilosella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, “ 
<emphasis id="B95BD2217F081E373C0AFD3DB4261E4D" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="400">
The species is undoubtedly a 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F75B07F081E3738CFFCD8B4261E4D" box="[151,256,773,796]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Stenaspis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Stenaspis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
,” however, the dense punctures and vestiture will amply distinguish it from 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F75B07F081E373C0FFCD8B1E61E4D" box="[1111,1216,773,796]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Stenaspis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95BD2217F081E373C0FFCD8B1E61E4D" box="[1111,1216,773,796]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="400">Stenaspis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3355DB87F081E37389FFCF5B6D51E34" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B900E337F081E37389FFCF5B6D51E34" blockId="49.[151,1437,151,869]" pageId="49" pageNumber="400">
<emphasis id="B95BD2217F081E37389FFCF5B4681E10" bold="true" box="[199,334,808,833]" pageId="49" pageNumber="400">Etymology.</emphasis>
The etymology of the name “ 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F75B07F081E373A9AFCF5B6711E10" box="[706,855,808,833]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Pilostenaspis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95BD2217F081E373A9AFCF5B6711E10" box="[706,855,808,833]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="400">Pilostenaspis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” is the Latin prefix 
<emphasis id="B95BD2217F081E373C00FCF5B1AB1E10" box="[1112,1165,808,833]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="400">pilo-</emphasis>
or “hairy”, and genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F75B07F081E3738CFFC90B4E41E34" authority="Audinet-Serville" authorityName="Audinet-Serville" box="[151,450,844,869]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Stenaspis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95BD2217F081E3738CFFC90B4261E35" box="[151,256,845,868]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="400">Stenaspis</emphasis>
Audinet-Serville
</taxonomicName>
where the species 
<taxonomicName id="4C2F75B07F081E373ACCFC91B7D21E34" box="[660,756,844,869]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Stenaspis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="49" pageNumber="400" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosella">
<emphasis id="B95BD2217F081E373ACCFC91B7D21E34" box="[660,756,844,869]" italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="400">pilosella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally placed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
